recordings.loc: Pleasant Springs (near  Cottage Grove), Dane County, Wisconsin
recordings.type: call, life stage uncertain, sex uncertain
recordings.rmk: Recording is not modified except from .wav to mp3.  Bird was in a pine tree and I was directly next to the pine tree (tree is ~25' tall), but could not see it.  Several (at least 2) of these birds have been calling back and forth for weeks.  In the early morning for certain, but I think we have heard them into the late morning or daytime also.  Not positive on that.  I have sent this sound file to several people and no one has a clue.  The cadence might suggest tufted titmouse, which we did have here this winter, but the actual sound does not.  I have another recording from the same day/time.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Two Blue Jays and an American Robin mobbing a Broad-winged Hawk. All three birds perched on bare limbs in the crown of a tree ~7m above the ground. Note harsh Blue Jay calls at 1:23 and 1:40 as the Blue Jay charged the hawk. Besides the occasional sallies by the Blue Jays, there was no other action or violence besides the calls. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sounds. Initially perched in privet in forest understory. Seemed to be harassing a Red-headed Woodpecker, following it from tree to tree and watching the woodpecker while calling. Multiple sounds including typical call, rattle/growl, and repeated mimicry of Red-shouldered Hawk. All RSHA calls in this cut are from the Blue Jay.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.rmk:
Recorded on iPhone 5 using EIM-001 microphone and RODE Rec app. Imported to Audacity with minor trim to shorten the gaps and eliminate "dead air". High Pass Filter to 2600Hz with a rolloff of 24dB to eliminate the nearby traffic noise.

Blue Jay was in an Oak about 25 feet above my head. 

It was communicating with other Jays in the area.  

Plumage was standard for the bird. Bright blues and very clean but nothing out of the ordinary.

Was interested in this spectrogram as it appears as a "barber pole". Initially I was wondering how they can make 7 notes but now it appears that they are 2 notes with multiple harmonics perhaps? This is a call that often bothers me to hear as it is usually drowning out a bird I am trying to listen to but in this case I did not appreciate the visual beauty behind it.

#Habitat#

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird perched in a cedar tree, initially making typical Blue Jay call and then engaging in soft song possibly mimicking several species including Cooper's Hawk (0:10), Mississippi Kite (0:12), Red-bellied Woodpecker (0:27), and American Goldfinch (0:46). The intermittent call (e.g., 0:14) sounds perhaps like a White-breasted Nuthatch. None of these species was present in the vicinity of the Blue Jay (see background species listed). 

#Habitat#
Light urban lawn adjoining a oak-hickory forest fragment with some large trees.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

recordings.rmk: Natural whisper song and 'bell call' from a presumed male about 3-4m up in Southern Magnolia in suburban neighborhood. It was idly hopping about the tree, mostly keeping out of sight while whisper-singing, and appeared to be alone. I could not see any stereotyped movements associated with the whisper song, and didn't want to move to get a better view, as I feared the bird may cease singing when seeing my movement. When bell-calling, it bowed its head exaggeratedly, and eventually captured an unidentified insect which it ate, occasionally pausing to bell-call.

recordings.loc: Algonquin Highlands, Haliburton County, Ontario
recordings.rmk: Hawk was being mobbed by and occaisionaly taking runs at a group of Blue Jays. To the point that I wasn't sure who was chasing who.  I am assuming the sound was coming from the hawk because it appeared to coincide with one of the sortees it would fly. This lasted for at least 15 minutes in the same tree on the edge of Mixed forest. Observed the same behaviour a day later at a different location (3km away) and have a 5 minute recording of the interaction. It could be the same hawk.
